We spent two full days in Granada, the site of the Alhambra. We made a night visit to the palace at the Alhambra and then toured the rest of the site, including the Generalife, the next day. In between we stuffed ourselves with tapas, local beer, and local ham.
We had a morning to explore Toulouse before our visit to Airbus. We visited the town centre, the Basilica, and a museum based in an old monastery.

We went on the Airbus 380 assembly line tour (no photos allowed) and viewed 380s being assembled and tested.
Later in the afternoon we had a private tour, thanks to no one else registering for the late afternoon English language Heritage Tour. We got up close and personal with the Caravelle - an early French passenger jet, and climbed on board one of the Air France Concordes, and one of Airbus's first passenger jets - an A300B.

Destination one on Big Wednesday in Provence was the town of Avignon. Avignon is famous for its papal palace, used when the pope was based in France, and also for its bridge. Needless to say, we spent time in the palace and sur le pont.
As part of Big Wednesday in Provence, we dropped in to the Pont du Gard - the famous remnant of a Roman acqueduct. It is big.

The walled town of 'dead waters'. en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aigues-Mortes On the way here we saw a great air formation show over Salon-de-Provence - complete with red, white and blue smoke trailsI think it must have been the Patrouille de France en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrouille_de_France Bonus. We drove through the Camargue, a water land with native white horses and farmed black bulls - used for bull fights. There is also lots of amazing bird life here, including flamingos, but unfortunately we didn't spot any of those (running out of time).

While driving through Provence on our way to Aix, we spotted an impressive looking monastery off the Autoroute and based on our guidebook's description, we decided to visit it.
We popped into the neighbouring cemetery first, and were surprised by the popularity of beautifully rendered ceramic flowers on the family mausoleums.
Being a public holiday, not much in the way of shopping was open, but a brasserie serving local cuisine was.
